Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

00:28.540 --> 00:33.860
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and
fantasy.

00:36.500 --> 00:38.220
And here are your hosts.

00:42.720 --> 00:50.980
This is Bill Vernon and Daryl Lane. One of today's most popular and prolific
science fiction authors is Fred Saberhagen. Saberhagen is best known for two

00:50.980 --> 00:59.680
series. One is a five-novel set on Dracula. The other consists of a novel in
over 30 stories on the Berserkers. As with many other science fiction writers,

01:00.060 --> 01:12.480
Saberhagen began by reading it. When I was very young, when I was like eight or
nine years old, I came upon this old pulp magazine, secondhand magazine

01:12.480 --> 01:18.580
someplace, and there were a couple of stories in there that really impressed me.
I think they scared the daylights out of me, actually.

01:21.360 --> 01:31.440
And magazines of that kind were prohibited for a very while from being brought
into the house. Then I just kind of went away from it for a few years. When I

01:31.440 --> 01:44.120
was about 16, I started haunting the secondhand magazine shops, which they then
had in Chicago, and picking up old copies of Astounding, as it was then called.

01:45.940 --> 02:01.840
And then I didn't really get into writing until later on. I was in the Air Force
in my 20s, and I had a lot of time on my hands. I would make a stab at it now

02:01.840 --> 02:21.200
and then. And still, I guess I didn't have access to a typewriter and all this
privacy and so on. And still nothing really came of it. And I was in, let's

02:21.200 --> 02:26.120
see, I was almost 30 before I actually sat

02:26.120 --> 02:37.620
down and seriously wrote a story and really typed out the manuscript properly
and got it, sent it off to be sold. Saberhagen has some interesting thoughts on

02:37.620 --> 02:46.740
science fiction and its relation to mainstream or regular literature. I guess
when you say mainstream, I guess I'm coming to think more and more of mainstream

02:46.740 --> 03:00.000
as kind of an offshoot of writing or literature or whatever you call it, where
you're limited to things

03:00.000 --> 03:10.160
that can only happen with a high probability in the next block or in the next
two months or something like that. And I think if you look back historically,

03:10.160 --> 03:23.100
most of the literature has really been wide open. You're allowed to use ghosts.
You're allowed to go to other planets. You can do all these things. We've

03:23.100 --> 03:33.140
somehow turned this around and put this in its own little ghetto. But I think it
really should be the other way. Sometimes the border between mainstream

03:33.140 --> 03:42.200
literature, the kind that deals with everyday reality, and science fiction
becomes vague. Reality can catch up with science fiction quickly. Saberhagen

03:42.200 --> 03:54.160
uses one of his own books, Octagon, published in 1981, to point this out. And
it's probably as close to a mainstream thing as I've ever done. It's set in the

03:54.160 --> 04:07.560
very near future, and it's largely about computers and programming and people
who play games with computers. And I guess when I started to write it, it was

04:07.560 --> 04:17.820
still science fiction, and by the time it's published, it may be just a little
out of date even. I don't know. Saberhagen talks about Dracula and the

04:17.820 --> 04:32.200
Berserkers, two of his most popular creations. I think what's got the biggest
reader response by far is the Dracula books I've done. I get more letters and

04:32.200 --> 04:46.960
mail and sometimes more money for one of those than for all the Berserkers. The
Berserkers have been around a long time, and a lot of people have picked

04:46.960 --> 04:56.600
up on them over the years, but they're not really what sells the most books now.
We'll have more on Fred Saberhagen tomorrow.

05:03.820 --> 05:11.660
This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show, a production of the Permian Basin
Science Fiction Association, produced in conjunction with Odessa College in

05:11.660 --> 05:12.420
Odessa, Texas.

05:54.540 --> 05:58.480
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

06:14.160 --> 06:19.500
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and
fantasy.

06:22.140 --> 06:23.860
And here are your hosts.

06:28.200 --> 06:36.940
This is Daryl Lane. And Bill Vernon. Fred Saberhagen has been a professional
science fiction author for some 17 years. His output is notable for its variety.

06:37.220 --> 06:49.320
Even though he writes typical science fiction, good science fiction such as the
popular Berserker series, he tries related areas too. I like to change back and

06:49.320 --> 07:02.520
forth, I think. I get a little tired of doing whatever it is I'm doing after a
long book, and then I like to do something as different as I can find from that.

07:03.420 --> 07:11.780
One of his novels that varies from straight science fiction is The Huge Empire
of the East, a story with the characteristics of science fantasy. Originally

07:11.780 --> 07:19.480
there were three books, The Broken Lands, The Black Mountains, and Changeling
Earth. And they came out some years earlier

07:23.020 --> 07:33.300
with split up among two different publishers, as it happened, the way problems
of publishing and everything being what they are. Magic works in the Empire of

07:33.300 --> 07:41.760
the East, and sorcery is an occupation. And this is so because the structure of
atoms has been changed, making nuclear power and technology impossible. But at

07:41.760 --> 07:51.240
the novel's end, there's a tremendous battle between inhuman forces. One is
Orcus, a demon power that represents the irrational into magic. The other is

07:51.240 --> 07:58.480
Ardna, a super machine which has gathered enough strength to challenge the
magical foundation of the world. The result of the battle is a balance.

07:58.480 --> 08:11.160
Technology and magic will coexist. The world was changing again, and at least
for a time, both of these kinds of powers would be functional. In 1976,

08:11.480 --> 08:20.000
Saberhagen published a horror story in the classic tradition, a mysterious
house, an unknown force haunting it, a family buying the house and moving in.

08:20.280 --> 08:33.520
The book is Specimens. Kind of a fun story, if you can call it that, of a menace
to be overcome. The old house in the story, by the way, really exists in

08:33.520 --> 08:46.700
Lombard. It did a few years ago. When we lived in Chicago, we were looking for
houses in the area there, and that was one that we looked at. The power haunting

08:46.700 --> 08:55.980
the house is an alien living beneath it. It's been there for centuries, even
before the house was built, capturing humans as specimens. It was an attempt to

08:55.980 --> 09:06.760
write a good grade B movie plot, and nobody's bought it yet to make a good grade
B movie, but there's a new Ace edition coming out in a few months here, and

09:06.760 --> 09:17.180
maybe somebody will. Another facet of Saberhagen's variety is seen in a little
-known satire, Love Conquers All, which came out in 1974. It extrapolates

09:17.180 --> 09:24.380
strongly from present social trends, and in that sense is reminiscent of Poul and
Kornbluth's advertising classic, The Space Merchants. But Saberhagen

09:24.380 --> 09:32.740
extrapolates from something very different than advertising. I guess it was the
controversy

09:32.740 --> 09:50.660
about abortion and sex, and things were bombarded, questions we're faced with
all the time here. And I just tried to, you know, the traditional science

09:50.660 --> 10:00.500
fiction writer's viewpoint, take a look at everything, turn everything inside
out, and see how it looks from the other point of view. In Love Conquers All,

10:00.620 --> 10:09.100
Saberhagen totally reverses all our present attitudes towards sex and love. The
book presents a world in which a wife should have affairs, in which virginity is

10:09.100 --> 10:20.240
horrifying. And, as a clever touch, the curses people use are words like purity
and chastity. We asked Saberhagen if the book had a message. Was it satire? Was

10:20.240 --> 10:26.860
he on a soapbox? No, I think

10:26.860 --> 10:35.280
that's your department, really. You know, whether it's satire or what it is, I
think I've, as I said, I think I've done my job when I've written it. So I

10:35.280 --> 10:43.260
wouldn't say you're wrong. Classify it however you will. Tomorrow, more of Fred
Saberhagen.

10:50.460 --> 10:58.360
This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show, a production of the Permian Basin
Science Fiction Association, produced in conjunction with Odessa College in

10:58.360 --> 10:59.120
Odessa, Texas.

11:43.580 --> 11:47.460
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

12:02.840 --> 12:08.200
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and
fantasy.

12:10.840 --> 12:12.560
And here are your hosts.

12:17.060 --> 12:26.220
This is Bill Vernon. And Daryl Lane. Dracula, the fearsome vampire of legend and
myth. You wouldn't think anything new could be written on him. But Science

12:26.220 --> 12:36.100
Fiction author Fred Saberhagen thought otherwise. So far, he's written five
novels on Dracula. The Dracula tape is the first one, which is a recounting of

12:36.100 --> 12:46.820
the original, Bram Stoker's original Dracula story, only seen from the point of
view of the count. And there's Holmes Dracula, and an old friend of the family,

12:47.660 --> 12:57.980
and Thorn, which is out now. Since we spoke with Saberhagen, the fifth book in
the series, Dominion, has come out. We asked him how he got interested in

12:57.980 --> 13:13.460
Dracula. Well, I just sat down one day, and just for fun, I wanted to reread the
original Dracula, which I had read once before, years earlier. And I think it's

13:13.460 --> 13:27.100
not all that good a book, really, apart from this titanic, devilish, central
character. But it struck me more and more as I read through it that Dracula was

13:27.100 --> 13:36.440
hardly ever on stage in this thing. Everybody's talking about him, and he's
almost always off somewhere doing something. Nobody quite knows what.

13:39.460 --> 13:49.180
So I guess maybe I had Rosencrantz and Guildenstern are dead on my mind or
something like that. But I just thought, what would it look like from the chief

13:49.180 --> 14:00.980
villain's point of view? So off I went. It was an awful lot of fun to write, and
it just seemed to go right along. The first book was The Dracula Tape, published

14:00.980 --> 14:10.520
in 1975. In this novel, Dracula is telling what really happened to Lucy,
Professor Van Helsing, and Jonathan, the characters from the Bram Stoker novel.

14:10.720 --> 14:19.400
As it turns out, the Count is a victim of circumstances, and Van Helsing is a
demented loony. In Saberhagen's account, the vampire almost never kills anyone.

14:19.400 --> 14:27.780
He just takes a quart to go. It was Van Helsing who was accidentally killing the
victims by giving them blood transfusions from persons whose blood type didn't

14:27.780 --> 14:36.480
match. And readers liked it. It was something different. Dracula from the
vampire's point of view. And Saberhagen had something different, even unique,

14:36.600 --> 14:47.100
for the sequel, entitled The Holmes Dracula File. The time came to think about
doing a sequel for it, and it occurred to me that nobody had ever put Holmes and

14:47.100 --> 15:00.440
Dracula in the same book up to that point, as far as I knew. And it seemed to me
they, this would be very interesting, it's as if they represented the two sides

15:00.440 --> 15:12.860
of the human psyche, or the intellect and the dark side. And here they were,
they were contemporaries, they were in the same city in the same year, and

15:12.860 --> 15:25.120
everybody knew about them both, and still they'd never, you know, they just
completely missed each other, so I decided I had to try to make contact there

15:25.120 --> 15:34.720
someplace. Can Saberhagen's Dracula material be considered science fiction? Its
popularity is obvious, but does it attract science fiction readers or some other

15:34.720 --> 15:47.600
type? Sometimes you see it on the fantasy shelf in the bookstore, sometimes you
see it in occult, sometimes you see it on the new shelf where all the zombies

15:47.600 --> 16:00.820
and haunted babies and all these modern, recent things appear. I don't really
care as long as people are reading it. I don't know if they're science fiction

16:00.820 --> 16:10.640
readers. Some of them think they're vampires. You get a pretty good, maybe some
of them are vampires. How do the Dracula books compare with Saberhagen's other

16:10.640 --> 16:26.080
books in terms of reader response? I think what's got the biggest reader
response by far is the Dracula books I've done. I get more letters and mail and

16:26.080 --> 16:30.560
sometimes more money. We'll have more on Fred Saberhagen tomorrow.

16:38.000 --> 16:46.000
This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show, a production of the Permian Basin
Science Fiction Association, produced in conjunction with Odessa College in

16:46.000 --> 16:46.760
Odessa, Texas.

17:31.140 --> 17:35.060
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

17:50.940 --> 17:56.200
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and
