17:58.880 --> 18:00.540
And here are your hosts.

18:04.960 --> 18:12.760
This is Daryl Lane and Bill Vernon. In the worlds of science fiction, the
deadliest enemies man has to face are the berserkers of Fred Saberhagen. The

18:12.760 --> 18:21.660
berserkers are machines, highly intelligent machines that are able to reproduce
and to repair themselves endlessly. They come in all sizes, from immense globes

18:21.660 --> 18:29.480
the size of worlds to robots or androids that simulate human beings. And they
are all deadly killing machines. Each berserker is programmed to do one thing

18:29.480 --> 18:39.460
and one thing only, to seek out and destroy all life. Author Saberhagen
discusses the origin of the term. Of course, the berserkers historically are the

18:39.460 --> 18:53.740
Norse warriors who would go mad and run around killing people until they were
killed. And I don't know why, it just seemed to come along with the original

18:53.740 --> 19:04.140
concept and I used it. The berserkers originated far in the past, before
humanity had achieved technology or space travel. There had been two super races

19:04.140 --> 19:11.800
engaged in interstellar war. One of them had produced and programmed the
berserker machines to annihilate its enemies. Now the two warring races have

19:11.800 --> 19:20.360
vanished, but the berserkers remain, fulfilling their function of searching out
and destroying all forms of life. Saberhagen recalls when he wrote his first

19:20.360 --> 19:35.860
berserker story. I was writing, let's see, back very early, in the early 1960s.
I was writing short stories, most of which were being published in Galaxy or

19:35.860 --> 19:49.120
Worlds of If, Worlds of Tomorrow. Fred Pohl was the editor then. And I had this
good idea for a short, kind of a puzzle short story. And I got about halfway

19:49.120 --> 19:59.240
through the story and I said, well, what sort of a villain will I have? And I
said, I know what sort of villain I'll have. I'll have this giant robotic

19:59.240 --> 20:15.020
spaceship, 50 miles in diameter, etc., etc. And I just looked around and there
it was. Saberhagen's editor, Frederik Pohl, liked the berserker idea. Fred Pohl

20:15.020 --> 20:24.180
really liked the berserker. He bought the story. He wasn't all that crazy about
the story, but he liked the berserker. And he said, why don't you do some more

20:24.180 --> 20:36.260
berserkers and have somebody go on one of these things and so on. And it's just
there for a while about all I wrote was berserkers. Since the 60s, Saberhagen

20:36.260 --> 20:45.220
has written some 30 berserker stories for various science fiction magazines.
Most have been collected in four volumes. Berserker, The Ultimate Enemy,

20:45.640 --> 20:55.520
Berserker Man, and The Berserker Wars. And he's also written one berserker
novel, Brother Assassin. Many of the berserker stories are related, with

20:55.520 --> 21:03.280
recurring characters or settings. They are also spread over a huge span of time,
thousands of years, so that Saberhagen can experiment with different human

21:03.280 --> 21:12.540
cultures and technologies as mankind battles its seemingly unstoppable enemy. We
asked Saberhagen if he had worked out a precise future history or timeline for

21:12.540 --> 21:24.240
the berserker material. What I've tried to do is just always leave plenty of
room in every direction. I have this war going on for thousands of years and

21:24.240 --> 21:36.380
over at least a good part of the galaxy. And I've never really... I guess if you
asked me about two different stories, I could probably tell you which one was

21:36.380 --> 21:50.160
supposed to come ahead of the other one. But I just wanted to avoid being too
limited. Fred Pohl thought I was about to wipe out all the berserkers there at

21:50.160 --> 22:03.200
one point. I did a story called Stone Place, where this huge berserker fleet was
destroyed. But I took care that some of them got away at least. The berserkers

22:03.200 --> 22:11.260
haven't been destroyed, so the battle is still going on. But Saberhagen isn't
sure he'll do any more stories on the material. Right now I don't have any

22:11.260 --> 22:17.040
special urge to write another berserker story. And I don't know if I ever will
or not.

